Here's how to wire it up:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // Data service — Singleton: reuse one HttpClient/connection pool app-wide
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // ViewModels — Transient: fresh state each time a page is created
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Pages — Transient: new instance per navigation
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why each lifetime:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Wraps `HttpClient`; one instance avoids socket exhaustion and lets you cache/share state (auth tokens, etc.) across the app. |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each navigation should get a clean VM with fresh state — avoids stale data leaking between visits. |
| Pages | **Transient** | Matches the VMs; a new page instance binds to its new VM. Avoids UI state pollution on re-navigation. |

**When you'd choose differently:**

- Use **Scoped** (via `AddScoped`) if you later adopt Shell-based navigation scopes where a VM should live for one "logical session" but not forever.
- Use **Singleton** for a VM only if the page is a persistent tab that should retain scroll position/state across the app lifetime.
